You are looking for [Functional Interfaces](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/util/function/package-summary.html). [`BinaryOperator`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/util/function/BinaryOperator.html) may be a good fit for your specific use case:

    public static String answer(Vector alpha, Vector beta, BinaryOperator&lt;Vector&gt; operator){
        return operator.apply(alpha, beta).toString();
    }

Assuming that the `Vector` class has a bunch of methods like the ones bellow:

    public Vector add(Vector other) { // ...
    }
   
    public Vector subtract(Vector other) { //...
    }

You can pass them around as method references:

    String firstAnswer = answer(alpha, beta, Vector::add);
    String secondAnswer = answer(alpha, beta, Vector::subtract);

PS: My code is following usual Java coding conventions. E.g., Class names use PascalCase and methods use camelCase. I highly suggest adopting the same conventions when writing Java code.

