answers.body_markdown:
## Side remark

&gt; (…) this docker-compose meant for production (…)

Beware, the lines

```
    ports:
      - ${DATABASE_PORT}:5432
```

are risky because it means the database will be reachable directly from the host.

This is unnecessary for the `api` service to reach the `db` service.

So, just remove this property if the configuration is intended for prod,
and add the following property in both services:

```
    networks:
      - app-network
```

## Suggestion for the main issue

It is difficult to suggest a direct fix for your issue because some info is lacking *and* the error looks fishy (it says *must start with &#39;jdbc&#39;* while it already starts with &#39;jdbc&#39;).

So, just let me suggest an alternative, simpler design:

1. Use less environment variables to specify the database URL and **don&#39;t include the Java-specific `jdbc:` prefix.**
2. Create a `DataSource` class (→ rely on regular Java programming instead of a mere `application.properties` file), thus following some idea from [this Baeldung tutorial](https://www.baeldung.com/spring-boot-configure-data-source-programmatic#configuring-a-datasource-bean).
3. And replace your `SPRING_PROFILES_ACTIVE=&quot;prod&quot; … docker-compose -f docker-compose.yml up -d` code with a simpler CLI command, with fewer variables and using `.env` files if need be.

Here is a complete setup example (under MIT license):

### Step 1

&gt; docker-compose.yml

```yaml
services:
  db:
    image: &#39;postgres:13&#39;
    environment:
      POSTGRES_DB: ${DATABASE_NAME}
      POSTGRES_USER: ${DATABASE_USER}
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: ${DATABASE_PASSWORD}
    networks:
      - app-network
    volumes:
      - app-db:/var/lib/postgresql/data

  api:
    image: ghcr.io/mycoolproject/apiproject:latest
    ports:
      - &#39;8080:8080&#39;
    environment:
      DATABASE_NO_SSL: &quot;true&quot;
      DATABASE_URL: ${DATABASE_POSTGRES_URL}
    networks:
      - app-network
    depends_on:
      - db
networks:
  app-network:
    driver: bridge
volumes:
  app-db:
    driver: local
```

&gt; .env (containing sensitive values)

```yaml
# If you edit DATABASE_NAME or USER or PASSWORD, also edit DATABASE_POSTGRES_URL.
DATABASE_NAME = &quot;mydb&quot;
DATABASE_USER = &quot;admin&quot;
DATABASE_PASSWORD = &quot;admin123&quot;
DATABASE_POSTGRES_URL = &quot;postgres://admin:admin123@db:5432/mydb&quot;
# Here: db is the docker-compose service identifier &amp; 5432 should always be 5432.
```

&gt; .gitignore

```
.env
```

### Step 2

&gt; DataConfig.java

```java
package project.app;

import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.jdbc.DataSourceBuilder;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;

import javax.sql.DataSource;
import java.net.URI;
import java.net.URISyntaxException;

@Configuration
public class DataConfig {

    @Bean
    public DataSource dataSource() throws URISyntaxException {
        String DBURL = System.getenv(&quot;DATABASE_URL&quot;);
        String NOSSL = System.getenv(&quot;DATABASE_NO_SSL&quot;);
        if (DBURL != null &amp;&amp; DBURL.length() &gt; 0) {
            URI dbUri = new URI(DBURL);
            String username = dbUri.getUserInfo().split(&quot;:&quot;)[0];
            String password = dbUri.getUserInfo().split(&quot;:&quot;)[1];
            String jdbcUrl = &quot;jdbc:postgresql://&quot; + dbUri.getHost() + &#39;:&#39; + dbUri.getPort() + dbUri.getPath()
                    + (&quot;true&quot;.equals(NOSSL) ? &quot;&quot; : &quot;?sslmode=require&quot;);
            System.err.println(&quot;*** DataConfig: jdbc:postgresql://_&quot;);
            DataSourceBuilder basicDataSource = DataSourceBuilder.create();
            basicDataSource.driverClassName(&quot;org.postgresql.Driver&quot;);
            basicDataSource.url(jdbcUrl);
            basicDataSource.username(username);
            basicDataSource.password(password);
            return basicDataSource.build();
        } else { // useful for in-memory test
            DataSourceBuilder basicDataSource = DataSourceBuilder.create();
            basicDataSource.driverClassName(&quot;org.h2.Driver&quot;);
            String jdbcUrl = &quot;jdbc:h2:mem:test&quot;;
            System.err.println(&quot;*** DataConfig: jdbc:h2:_&quot;);
            basicDataSource.url(jdbcUrl);
            basicDataSource.username(&quot;TODO&quot;);
            basicDataSource.password(&quot;&quot;);
            return basicDataSource.build();
        }
    }
}
```

### Step 3

Just run:

```sh
docker compose config  # to check variables interpolation
docker compose up -d   # to run the stack
```

Indeed: `-f docker-compose.yml` is always unnecessary, and `DATABASE_USER=&quot;admin&quot; …` is always parsed from the `.env` file.

